---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const groupsSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "SportsEvent",
  "name": "World Cup 2026 Group Stage Draw",
  "description": "Analysis of the 12 groups for the expanded 48-team FIFA World Cup.",
  "startDate": "2026-06-11"
};
---

<Layout 
  title="FIFA World Cup 2026 Groups: The 48-Team Draw Explained" 
  description="Forget everything you know about the World Cup. 12 groups. 48 teams. We break down the new group stage format and how teams advance."
  schema={groupsSchema}
>
  <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-black mb-6 text-blue-900 tracking-tight">The New 12-Group Era</h1>
  
  <article class="prose lg:prose-lg max-w-none mb-10 text-gray-700">
    <p>Forget the classic 32-team format we grew up with. The FIFA World Cup 2026 groups are entirely different. 48 nations. 12 groups of four. It's a massive shift in how the early stages of the tournament are played.</p>
    
    <p>Why does this matter? Because the math changed. Taking the top two from each group wasn't enough to build the next bracket. So, the eight best third-placed teams will now survive the group stage. This single rule change kills the "dead rubber" matches. Going into matchday 3, almost every single team will still have a mathematical shot at the knockouts.</p>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-100 rounded-xl p-6 my-8">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-blue-900 mt-0 mb-3">Group Stage Survival Guide</h2>
      <ul class="space-y-2 m-0 text-blue-800">
        <li><strong>Winner & Runner-up:</strong> Guaranteed spot in the Round of 32.</li>
        <li><strong>3rd Place:</strong> You sweat. The top 8 third-place finishers advance based on points and goal difference.</li>
        <li><strong>4th Place:</strong> Ticket home.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>